  "original_title": "\u0da9\u0dd3\u0dc3\u0dbd\u0dca \u0db1\u0dd0\u0dc0 \u0da2\u0dd4\u0dbd\u0dd2 \u0daf\u0dd9\u0dc0\u0dd0\u0db1\u0dd2 \u0dc3\u0dad\u0dd2\u0dba\u0dda - \u0db4\u0dd9\u0da7\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\u0dbd\u0dca \u0db1\u0dd0\u0dc0 \u0da2\u0dd4\u0dbd\u0dd2 \u0d85\u0db1\u0dca\u0dad\u0dd2\u0db8 \u0dc3\u0dad\u0dd2\u0dba\u0dda",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Diesel ship in the second week of July - Petrol ship in the last week of July",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Sagala Ratnayake, Chairman of the Committee appointed by Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe and Chief of Staff to the Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe has stated that a ship carrying diesel stocks is scheduled to return to Sri Lanka in the second week of July.",
        "Accordingly, 30,000 metric tons of diesel is scheduled to return to Sri Lanka between July 11-15, he said. He added that the return of the fuel consignment was due after July 22. Until then, there are no oil tankers ordered by Sri Lanka, he said.",
        "However, arrangements are being made to obtain fuel tankers to Sri Lanka before these dates, using the links with the Ceylon Petroleum Corporation, he said."
      ],
